    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_3691305667" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/3691305667" />
    <a title="David" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/938229-david"><img alt="David" src="https://s.gr-assets.com/assets/nophoto/user/m_50x66-82093808bca726cb3249a493fbd3bd0f.png" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/3691305667?book_show_action=true">Dec 12, 2020</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="David" class="user" itemprop="url" name="David" href="/user/show/938229-david">David</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/938229-david?shelf=completed">completed</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer3691305667" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer3629064176877458731">The greatest achievement of this book is probably not what the author intended. The author probably wanted the reader to think about the horror of war and the fear of the enemy. However, what this author managed to do, as few can actually do, was to make me feel the cold winter and see the lush landscape. The author also manages to create an atmosphere, draw upon historical military details, and turn his prose into a transporter, dropping the reader into the Ardennes forest in the Winter of 1944</span>
  <span id="freeText3629064176877458731" style="display:none">The greatest achievement of this book is probably not what the author intended. The author probably wanted the reader to think about the horror of war and the fear of the enemy. However, what this author managed to do, as few can actually do, was to make me feel the cold winter and see the lush landscape. The author also manages to create an atmosphere, draw upon historical military details, and turn his prose into a transporter, dropping the reader into the Ardennes forest in the Winter of 1944. <br /><br />A small squad of American soldiers is assigned to a forward position in the Ardennes with instructions to set up an observation post in appears to be an abandoned Chateau. The Chateau is empty and the men are excited about what they believe is going to be easy duty. They are pleased to be out of foxholes and to have a roof over their heads and a fireplace. It's dull duty, and the guys create all sorts of games to pass the time. I was impressed at the depth in which the author described the manner in which the soldiers were passing time. <br /><br />Of course, a story requires more than simply interesting details. After a few nights, they hear German voices laughing and calling. What is most frightening is that the Germans are obviously calling to them. Hunkered down and prepared to fight, the soldiers experience the tension of imminent combat, that never arrives. The Germans call out what appears to be something along the line of "sleep tight" and wander off into the darkness, laughing and singing. <br /><br />From this point forward, squad leader Will Knott, has to determine is it a German trick, were they being taunted, or do these particular Germans want to establish a private cease fire. The Americans even wonder if the war is over. This gives the novel most of its tension. It wouldn't be a very good war novel if there wasn't some fighting, and there is some. The author's focus is on the day-to-day survival activity, the tension of the nearby Germans, and the interpersonal relationships of the soldiers. <br /><br />Wharton's story is compelling. His research into military equipment and ways to adapt even such items as the cardboard boxes left from the K-rations is very commendable. His details about keeping the jeeps ready to start in case of emergency departure demonstrate that he plunged into the research pool head first. A major strength of this novel is its ability to help the reader picture it in his mind and that must stem from a large amount of careful research. <br /><br />However compelling the story is meant to be, the characters are also very strong. The author manages to summon a squad of characters who are unique from one another. Despite the rich variety, these men are all determined to do one thing and that's survive. Novels such as this almost always feature a scene where two characters sit and discuss life in general, revealing something previously unknown about themselves to one another. This happens in nearly every war novel. Not that it suggests an overused cliche. The reason that it happens in pretty much every war novel is because it happened in real life over and over. <br /><br />The richness of the characterization and military details, however, is not enough to cause this to be the great American War novel. Wharton's writing style choice is meant to make the reader feel like it is all going on around him-right now. He chooses to write in the first person and the present tense. The intent seems to be to write as if the narrator is telling this story around a campfire to his grandkids or something. There is far too much detail for this style of writing. It's good writing, but at times, it just doesn't fit properly. <br /><br />A Midnight Clear is a good, but not great novel. It allows the reader to slip into the foxhole, the jeep and the forward observation post. It shows us the type of men who fought during the conflict. If you are looking for lots of action it isn't here, this one focuses on historicity and characterization.</span>
  <a data-text-id="3629064176877458731" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


      <div class="reviewFooter uitext buttons">
          

