  <div class="friendReviews elementListBrown" >
    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_3528641452" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/3528641452" />
    <a title="Steven Haywood Yaskell" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/16068436-steven-haywood-yaskell"><img alt="Steven Haywood Yaskell" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1357277559p2/16068436.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/3528641452?book_show_action=true">Sep 02, 2020</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Steven Haywood Yaskell" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Steven Haywood Yaskell" href="/user/show/16068436-steven-haywood-yaskell">Steven Haywood Yaskell</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was amazing"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was amazing</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer3528641452" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer18266758005804136762">The professional American writers of the period in which William Wharton (Albert Du Aime) lived for the most part were poetasters to the fine art of combat - Mailer and Jones being principle and very visible, muscular, Hemingway-esque exceptions. Du Aime was not a professional war novelist in this competition, but he had credentials to the act of actually being a shooting contestant in the non-literary fight between the major literary gladiators, when, in his later years, he wrote this magnifice</span>
  <span id="freeText18266758005804136762" style="display:none">The professional American writers of the period in which William Wharton (Albert Du Aime) lived for the most part were poetasters to the fine art of combat - Mailer and Jones being principle and very visible, muscular, Hemingway-esque exceptions. Du Aime was not a professional war novelist in this competition, but he had credentials to the act of actually being a shooting contestant in the non-literary fight between the major literary gladiators, when, in his later years, he wrote this magnificent tale of his wartime fight. Du Aime was not a major gladiator in this literary contest - the "best war novel," begun in America inadvertently by Stephen Crane and ending, intentionally, with Hemingway - who tried, but failed (not to deplore Hemingway's literary and especially linguistic talent and innovation to the art). But in the long run, Du Aime may just have equaled Crane, here. Most of all, he was a near-innocent dragged by the needs of the service &amp; typical military and bureaucratic incompetence, into a savage fight. He was relegated to this position by more than a little cowardice on behalf of his fellow citizens, and it is shown in technicolor in this work. <br /><br />It is for this reason we should be very grateful for the errors that lead such a person into an actual fight of the magnitude in which - like Erich Maria Remarque - Du Aime witnessed, fought, and survived. (Note: the background tone of this book is very much like All Quiet On The Western Front.) We have a simple, intelligent, kind soul who - due to the vagaries of changed promises in the middle of a brutal, socialist/royalist-inspired war - wound up briefly as a "dog-faced soldier" and, even if he was inherently not one, was at least able to write their story from a position so close he could not miss. Du Aime's journey in WWII was not so very unlike Remarque's, and, as kindred spirits, the naivete of the American drawn into a war by Germans, forces the same human story as Remarque's out of this American author. The experiences tie the two men so closely together as authors and as men, it heals the wounds of two world wars in these pages in a most nuanced and beautiful, humane manner.<br /><br />Promised college training and being saved for post-war college-level reconstruction work in applied sciences and as history recorders, etc., by Henry Stimson, the blithering incompetence that is endemic to the American civilian-led-by-professional (read: wealthy) cadre of West Point/Annapolis officers devolved into the "needs of the service" by the main procurer of personnel and materiel, General McNair. In the end, as the magic ball is passed, many of these "ASTPRs" get handed private stripes and guns, instead of officer's commissions and slide rules. It is a great thing that such things occur rarely in America: for the socialist/royalist (both &amp; the same) forces of eternal warfare had to be blunted somewhere. WWII's end meant the end of royalty and war-as-policy for achieving political ends forever. In a way, the tremors of this war still reverberate in the form of academic socialists and blunted royalists banging at the US's door in the form of European "Union" and UN tyranny. But, this will ebb away.<br /><br />In this novel, we see Henry Fleming's final lesson: that massed war leads to mass destruction so profound, the inner mind is shown as equally shattered as the surroundings in which the person walks. <br /><br />No puke-filled "anti-war" drama label here to suit the politics of the American Writer's Union. With A Midnight Clear, we have explored for us not just the utter stupidity of war, but its inevitability - couched in a clear, beautiful warning: NO MORE. </span>
  <a data-text-id="18266758005804136762" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


      <div class="reviewFooter uitext buttons">
          

