<span id="freeTextContainer10430578500106215572">I enjoyed this.<br/><br/>Wharton writes like he&apos;s sat there telling you a story: &quot;I&apos;ve got mud all over my boots and I&apos;m slipping in the snow as I try to get to the foxhole&quot; - that kind of thing. I like that approach.<br/>The story is a sad one, it&apos;s a short journey for the reader from &quot;Band of Brothers&quot;-style opening in the Ardennes, through an almost fairy tale period of snow-covered woodland and a ruined chateau, to a shocking conclusion which leaves the reader thinking &quot;yeah, I can imagine how that&apos;s just </span>
  <span id="freeText10430578500106215572" style="display:none">I enjoyed this.<br /><br />Wharton writes like he's sat there telling you a story: "I've got mud all over my boots and I'm slipping in the snow as I try to get to the foxhole" - that kind of thing. I like that approach.<br />The story is a sad one, it's a short journey for the reader from "Band of Brothers"-style opening in the Ardennes, through an almost fairy tale period of snow-covered woodland and a ruined chateau, to a shocking conclusion which leaves the reader thinking "yeah, I can imagine how that's just what would happen". It's about young, inexperienced men forced into situations they haven't been alive long enough to deal with, yet having to live with the consequences of their inability to process events for the rest of their lives.<br /><br />It's a story which leads you to one of two conclusions: 1. war is universally bad, stupid and pointless, or 2. soldiers really ought to be old men who move slowly and with purpose.</span>
  <a data-text-id="10430578500106215572" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


