<span id="freeTextContainer9221190427397133307">3rd January 1999<br/>William Wharton<br/>A Midnight Clear<br/><br/>I read this in the autumn, about the same time as Robert Greaves “Goodbye to all that”.<br/><br/>Two wars, two intelligent young men sent out as cannon fodder. Greaves, the British upper middle class in the First World War and Wharton the American genius in the Second World War.<br/>Wharton tells a hard story with a romantic ending in a lighthearted American way. Greaves was bitter when he wrote his book, much more aware and much less willing to accept the waste o</span>
  <span id="freeText9221190427397133307" style="display:none">3rd January 1999<br />William Wharton<br />A Midnight Clear<br /><br />I read this in the autumn, about the same time as Robert Greaves “Goodbye to all that”.<br /><br />Two wars, two intelligent young men sent out as cannon fodder. Greaves, the British upper middle class in the First World War and Wharton the American genius in the Second World War.<br />Wharton tells a hard story with a romantic ending in a lighthearted American way. Greaves was bitter when he wrote his book, much more aware and much less willing to accept the waste of life caused by the incompetent generals and the political imperatives.<br />Wharton pokes fun at the generals, and his characters crack up and go mad. But there is always a lighthearted flippancy in his approach, no heartfelt bitterness. “Have a nice day” even in war.<br /></span>
